===Etymology===
From {{etyl|bat-pro|lv}} {{recons|dar-bas|lang=bat-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|lv}} {{recons|der-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|dar-||to tear, to split|lang=ine-pro}}. The original meaning was, according to some researchers, “till,” “plow” (cf. {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|дерба||breaking; newly ploughed field|tr=derbá|lang=ru}}; the object of this work is {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|torf|lang=non}}, {{term|torfa||turf, sod, peat|lang=non}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Torf||peat|lang=de}}, {{etyl|en|-}} {{term|turf|lang=en}}, which has the same origin as {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|дёрн||sod, turf|tr=djorn|lang=ru}}) or, according to others, “wicker-work, wattling, weaving” (cf. {{etyl|be|-}} {{term|дораб||basket|tr=dórab|lang=be}} (< Proto-Slavic {{recons|dorbь|lang=sla-pro}}), {{term|доровиць||tr=doróvits'|to bend|lang=be}}). Cognates include {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|darbas|dárbas|lang=lt}}. <ref>Karulis, Konstantīns. 1992, 2001. ''Latviešu etimoloģijas vārdnīca.'' Rīga: AVOTS. ISBN 9984700127.</ref>

